$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/hassall.html","<p>Hassall’s corpuscles are large (up to 100 um!), keratinized concentric aggregates of thymic epithelial cells found in the medulla. Although their function is not completely understood, they do secrete</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"15\" hint=\"13\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><p>that promote T-lymphocyte development.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/hassall.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"hassall\"></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'3\'})\">Go back to reconsider the supportive stroma of the thymus</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/inherent.html","<p>Inherent immunity is a synonym for innate immunity. Other terms to describe this form of natural, immediate defense include: genetic immunity, native immunity, natural immunity, and nonspecific immunity.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'4\'})\">Go back and reflect on lymphocytes and immunity</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/innate.html","<p>Innate immunity includes nonspecific, immediate defenses, which do not include lymphocytes.</p><p class=\"bold\">List examples of innate immunity throughout the body.</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'4\'})\">Go back and reflect on lymphocytes and immunity</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/lymph-node.html","<p>Lymph nodes have a capsule extending trabeculae into the parenchyma that is densely packed with lymphocytes. Lymph nodes also have morphologically distinct regions, however notice the lack of a paracortex, medullary cords, medullary sinuses, and lymphoid follicles in the patient’s slide that are seen in lymph nodes. <span class=\"bold\">Can you label the following lymph node slide?</span></p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-LymphNode-Image_ER-Palatine-Tonsil.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"lymph node\"></figure><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2 col-lg-offset-1\"><label>A.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"1\" hint=\"0\" ng-model=\"userAnswerA\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2\"><label>B.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"2\" hint=\"1\" ng-model=\"userAnswerB\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2\"><label>C.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"3\" hint=\"2\" ng-model=\"userAnswerC\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-sm-offset-2 col-lg-offset-0 col-lg-2\"><label>D.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"4\" hint=\"3\" ng-model=\"userAnswerD\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2\"><label>E.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"5\" hint=\"4\" ng-model=\"userAnswerE\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to investigate the slide from the mysterious mediastinal mass</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/paracortex.html","<p>The paracortex is found in lymph nodes situated between the outer cortex and inner medulla.</p><p class=\"bold\">Although immature thymocytes cannot leave the thymus, mature T-lymphocytes can enter the paracortex of lymph nodes through what unique blood vessels?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"21\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Paracortex.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'5\'})\">Return to determine where naïve lymphocytes travel to next</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/parathyroid.html","<p>Parathyroid glands also have a connective tissue capsule that extends septa into the gland like the patient’s slide exhibits. However, the parathyroid glands consist of densely packed clusters of <span class=\"italic\">principal (chief) cells</span> that secrete <span class=\"italic\">parathyroid hormone (PTH)</span> in response to decreased blood calcium levels.</p><p class=\"bold\">PTH binds receptors on osteoblasts. What paracrine factor is secreted by osteoblasts that stimulate osteoclasts?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"6\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Parathyroid2.jpg\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"parathyroid\"><figcaption>Source: <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//www.nature.com/nrrheum/journal/v7/n11/fig_tab/nrrheum.2011.130_F2.html\">http://www.nature.com/nrrheum/journal/v7/n11/fig_tab/nrrheum.2011.130_F2.html</a></figcaption></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to investigate the slide from the mysterious mediastinal mass</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/secondary.html","<p>Remember that secondary lymphoid organs include the spleen, lymph nodes, and MALT. Dense aggregations of MALT can be found in which layer of the gastrointestinal tract?</p><div class=\"row margin-top clearfix\" id=\"multChoice\"><div class=\"list-item col-xs-12\"><label><input type=\"radio\" name=\"choice\" value=\"A\">A) Mucosa and Submucosa</label></div><div class=\"list-item col-xs-12\"><label><input type=\"radio\" name=\"choice\" value=\"B\">B) Muscularis externa</label></div><div class=\"list-item col-xs-12\"><label><input type=\"radio\" name=\"choice\" value=\"C\">C) Serosa and Adventitia</label></div><div class=\"list-item col-xs-12\"><label><input type=\"radio\" name=\"choice\" value=\"D\">D) All of the above</label></div></div><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'2\'})\">Reevaluate the thymus classification as a lymphoid organ</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/sub-sinus.html","<p>The subcapsular sinus is found under the connective tissue capsule of lymph nodes. This sinus accepts lymph from the afferent lymphatic vessels.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Sub-Sinus.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'5\'})\">Return to determine where naïve lymphocytes travel to next</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/tertiary.html","<p>Remember that lymphoid organs are only described as primary and secondary.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'2\'})\">Reevaluate the thymus classification as a lymphoid organ</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/thymocytes.html","<p>Thymocytes (aka: T-lymphoblasts) are concentrated in the thymic medulla surrounded by macrophages and thymic epithelial cells (TECs). Thymocytes will eventually differentiate into mature, circulating T-lymphocytes.</p><div class=\"margin-top\"><p class=\"bold\">Would you describe the staining of thymocytes as basophilic or eosinophilic?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"16\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"margin-top\"><p class=\"bold\">Explain your choice.</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Thymocytes.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"thymocytes\"></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'3\'})\">Go back to reconsider the supportive stroma of the thymus</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/ans/thyroid.html","<p>The thyroid gland is composed of numerous epithelial <span class=\"italic\">thyroid follicles</span> each composed of a central colloid-filled lumen (containing large gelatinous proteins known as thyroglobulin, which are precursors to thyroid hormones) surrounded by <span class=\"italic\">follicular cells</span>. <span class=\"italic\">Parafollicular (C) cells</span> are located within and between follicles and secrete <span class=\"italic\">calcitonin</span> in response to high blood calcium levels.</p><p class=\"bold\">Follicular cells are what specific type of epithelium?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"0\" hint=\"55\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Thyroid.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"thyroid\"></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to investigate the slide from the mysterious mediastinal mass</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/pg/1.html","<p>A 33-year-old male presents with ptosis (drooping eyelid), trouble masticating and swallowing, and notices he feels fatigued quickly. An anterior mediastinal mass, 3.5cm in diameter, was found after a CT scan. Histological analysis after biopsy resulted in the slide below.</p><figure><img src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/mm-pg1.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"Responsive image\"></figure><p>You conclude the mass originated from:</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'thyroid\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Thyroid</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'lymph-node\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Lymph node</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'thymus\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Thymus</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'parathyroid\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Parathyroid</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/pg/2.html","<p>Correct! The thymus has a thin capsule that extends CT septa into the parenchyma separating the cortex and medulla into incomplete lobules. <span class=\"bold\">Can you label the following thymus slide?</span></p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Pg-2.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"thymus\"></figure><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>A.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"7\" hint=\"5\" ng-model=\"userAnswerA\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>B.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"8\" hint=\"6\" ng-model=\"userAnswerB\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>C.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"9\" hint=\"7\" ng-model=\"userAnswerC\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>D.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"10\" hint=\"8\" ng-model=\"userAnswerD\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><p class=\"bold margin-top-lg\">The thymus is considered a ________________ lymphoid organ.</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'primary\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Primary</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'secondary\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Secondary</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'tertiary\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Tertiary</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/pg/3.html","<p>Correct! Primary lymphoid organs include the thymus and<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"14\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Pg3.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></figure><p class=\"margin-top\">What is the function of the thymus?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"margin-top-lg\">Although considered a primary lymphoid organ, the thymus does not contain a stroma of reticulin fibers like many lymphoid organs. Instead, the supporting stroma arises from:</p><div class=\"row margin-top clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'hassall\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Hassall’s corpuscles</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'epi-cells\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Epithelioreticular cells</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'thymocytes\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Thymocytes</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/pg/4.html","<p>Correct! Epithelioreticular cells (aka: <span class=\"bold\">thymic epithelial cells, TECs</span>) surround developing T-lymphocytes (known as thymocytes). Together both cells types make up the thymic stroma.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Pg4.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></figure><p class=\"bold\">Thymic epithelial cells (TECs) in the cortex have 4 important functions:</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>1.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"alert\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>2.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"alert\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>3.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"alert\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>4.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"alert\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><p class=\"margin-top\">Thymic epithelial cells surround differentiating thymocytes (T-lymphoblasts) in the cortex.<br><span class=\"bold\">Lymphoblasts are considered a component of:</span></p><div class=\"row margin-top clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'innate\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Innate Immunity</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'adaptive\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Adaptive Immunity</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'inherent\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Inherent Immunity</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/pg/5.html","<p>Correct! <span class=\"bold\">Adaptive immunity</span>, also known as acquired immunity, develops gradually over time in response to specific <span class=\"italic\">antigens</span> (such as proteins, polysaccharides or molecular components of bacteria, viruses, or tumor cells) displayed on antigen presenting cells (APCs) and presented to B- and T-lymphocytes.</p><p class=\"bold margin-top\">Why is this system slow to respond initially but faster with subsequent infections?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"margin-top\">Although T-lymphoblasts (thymocytes) develop and mature in the thymus, they do not originate there.</p><p class=\"bold\">Where are these cells originally created?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"14\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><div class=\"img-split margin row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><ul class=\"left\"><li>Thymocytes that arrive to the thymus are considered to be in the double-negative stage and do not posses a T-cell receptor (TCR), CD4, or CD8 glycoproteins until they proliferate and begin differentiation in the cortex.</li><li>Eventually both CD4 and CD8 are expressed (double-positive stage).</li><li>These naïve thymocytes are schooled before they are released into circulation, undergoing a two-stage selection process that begins in the cortex with positive (clonal) selection.</li></ul></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><figure><img class=\"img-responsive\" ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/mm-positive-selection.png\"><figcaption>Source: <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//accessiblebiosci.blogspot.com/2013/08/negative-selectivi-t-dzhagalov-et-al.html\">http://accessiblebiosci.blogspot.com/2013/08/negative-selectivi-t-dzhagalov-et-al.html</a></figcaption></figure></div></div><p class=\"bold margin-top\">What events occur during positive selection?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"bold margin-top\">If lymphocytes pass the positive selection test in the thymic cortex, they move onto their next test in the:</p><div class=\"row margin-top clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'sub-sinus\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Subcapsular Sinus</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'paracortex\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Paracortex</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'medulla\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Medulla</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/pg/6.html","<div class=\"img-split row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><p>Awesome! Those lymphocytes that recognize MHC pass the positive selection test in the cortex and move onto the negative selection (clonal deletion) test in the medulla.</p><p class=\"bold\">What is negative selection?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><figure><img class=\"img-responsive\" ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/mm-negative-selection.png\"><figcaption>Source: <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//accessiblebiosci.blogspot.com/2013/08/negative-selectivi-t-dzhagalov-et-al.html\">http://accessiblebiosci.blogspot.com/2013/08/negative-selectivi-t-dzhagalov-et-al.html</a></figcaption></figure></div></div><h3>Histo Scavenger Hunt!</h3><p>Take a snapshot of a thymic (Hassall’s) corpuscle in the medulla, from <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//medsci.indiana.edu/junqueira/virtual/msci_76_5.html\">Slide 76: Thymus, H&amp;E.</a></p><p class=\"margin-top-lg\">Normally the thymus involutes with age.</p><p class=\"bold\">Compare <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//medsci.indiana.edu/histo/virtual/msci_123.html\">Slide 123 Thymus, H&amp;E</a> and <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://medsci.indiana.edu/histo/virtual/msci_126.html\">Slide 126 Thymus, H&amp;E</a>, then describe what occurs during involution of an organ.</p><div class=\"margin\"><mboa-input type=\"alert\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></div><div class=\"row margin clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Pg6-Slide123.png\"></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Pg6-Slide126.png\"></div></div><p class=\"back-link\">The results from a blood test that you ordered are in. <a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'7\'})\">Go check-in with your patient.</a></p>");
$templateCache.put("a-mysterious-mass/pg/7.html","<div class=\"img-split medium row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><p>The results of a blood test detected acetylcholine receptor (AchR) antibodies. Based on the symptoms your patient is experiencing in conjunction with the histological analysis leads you to diagnose myasthenia gravis from thymoma.</p><p>Thymomas are neoplasms derived from thymic epithelial cells that can display skeletal muscle protein epitopes (including acetylcholine receptors, ryanodine receptors, and titin).</p></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><figure><img class=\"img-responsive\" ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-Pg7.png\" alt=\"myasthenia-gravis\"><figcaption>Source: <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//www.beverlydoc.com/our-services/myasthenia-gravis/\">http://www.beverlydoc.com/our-services/myasthenia-gravis/</a></figcaption></figure></div></div><p class=\"bold\">Explain how a T-lymphocyte problem from the thymus contributes to antibody production that is targeting muscle seen in myasthenia gravis.</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"back-link\">You advise for a <a class=\"popup-video\" href=\"//www.youtube.com/watch?v=VylU8SFE6R4\">thymectomy</a> (complete surgical resection of the thymus). The thoracoscopic operation was successful. Surgical margins were negative and there was no evidence of macroscopic or microscopic capsular invasion. Intravenous infusion of immunoglobulin G (IgG) helped to remove circulating pathogenic antibodies and the patient improved.</p><p class=\"back-link margin-top-lg\">Nice work! <a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to the beginning of the case and play again!</a> Try selecting other options to verify you understand <span class=\"italic\">why</span> an answer was incorrect before moving on.</p>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/b-lymph.html","<p>B-cells form primary and secondary lymphoid nodules (follicles) adjacent to the central artery, but not PALS. Larger lymphoid nodules may contain a germinal center, displacing the central arteriole to the nodule’s periphery (see Junqueira, 13th Ed., Fig. 14-23b).</p><p class=\"bold\">Can you label the following slide of a secondary lymphoid follicle in the spleen?</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/NER-PAL-B-Cells.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"></figure><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>A.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"25\" ng-model=\"userAnswerA\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>B.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"26\" ng-model=\"userAnswerB\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>C.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"27\" ng-model=\"userAnswerC\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'6\'})\">Go back to reconsider the cells forming PALS.</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/flow1.html","<ol><li>Splenic artery &rarr; trabecular artery &rarr; central arteriole &rarr; penicillar arteriole &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">ensheathed capillary</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">splenic sinus</span> &rarr; red pulp vein &rarr; trabecular vein &rarr; splenic vein</li></ol><p>Note that this option goes directly from the ensheathed capillary to the splenic sinus without going through the splenic cords, which is seen in <span class=\"italic\">closed circulation</span>.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'4\'})\">Go back and reassess open circulation order</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/flow2.html","<ol start=\"2\"><li>Splenic artery &rarr; <span class=\"red\">trabecular artery</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">penicillar arteriole</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">central arteriole</span> &rarr; ensheathed capillary &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">splenic sinus</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">splenic cord</span> &rarr; red pulp vein &rarr; trabecular veins &rarr; splenic vein</li></ol><p>This choice left out the trabecular artery, reversed the arterioles, and reversed the flow through the splenic sinus and splenic cord.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'4\'})\">Go back and reassess open circulation order</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/flow4.html","<ol start=\"4\"><li>Splenic artery &rarr; trabecular artery &rarr; central arteriole &rarr; penicillar arteriole &rarr; ensheathed capillary &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">splenic sinus</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">splenic cord</span> &rarr; red pulp vein &rarr; trabecular vein &rarr; splenic vein</li></ol><p>Notice that this option reverses the order of flow through the cord and sinus that is seen in open circulation.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'4\'})\">Go back and reassess open circulation order</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/ll.html","<p>Peyer’s patches are prominent in the submucosa of the ileum (the terminal part of the small intestine) and are composed of groups of lymphoid follicles. Lymphoid follicles are mainly B-lymphocytes and are examples of MALT (mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue) protecting the mucosal surface of the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and urogenital tracts.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/Night-ER-Ans-II.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to slides</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/lr.html","<p>Lymph nodes have a cortex and medulla, with lymphoid nodules composed mainly of B-lymphocytes in the cortex and cords of cells separated by sinuses in the medulla. However, lymph nodes filter lymph, not blood, and would not produce the profuse bleeding that the patient is experiencing.</p><p class=\"bold\">Can you label the following lymph node slide?</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/MM-LymphNode-Image_ER-Palatine-Tonsil.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"></figure><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2 col-lg-offset-1\"><label>A.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"1\" hint=\"0\" ng-model=\"userAnswerA\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2\"><label>B.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"2\" hint=\"1\" ng-model=\"userAnswerB\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2\"><label>C.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"3\" hint=\"2\" ng-model=\"userAnswerC\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-sm-offset-2 col-lg-2 col-lg-offset-0\"><label>D.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"4\" hint=\"3\" ng-model=\"userAnswerD\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4 col-lg-2\"><label>E.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"5\" hint=\"4\" ng-model=\"userAnswerE\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to slides</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/macrophages.html","<p>Macrophages are abundant within splenic cords of the red pulp and ensheath penicillar arterioles.</p><p class=\"bold\">What is the function of these cells in the spleen?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'6\'})\">Go back to reconsider the cells forming PALS.</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/operate.html","<p>Although non-operative management is preferred in an attempt to save splenic function and avoid the risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI), the patient’s vitals indicate he is hemodynamically unstable and in an emergency situation. If instead the patient’s vital signs are less severe (hemodynamically stable), a CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis may be done to evaluate potential trauma and decide on further medical treatment.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'3\'})\">Go back and reassess the patient’s vitals.</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/primary.html","<p>Note that primary lymphoid organs include the bone marrow and the ____________?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"24\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'5\'})\">Reevaluate the spleen\'s classification as a lymphoid organ.</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/tertiary.html","<p>Note that lymphoid organs are only described as primary and secondary.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'5\'})\">Reevaluate the spleen\'s classification as a lymphoid organ.</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/ul.html","<p>Although lymphatic follicles are present, notice the lack of a distinct capsule and the specific tissue in the upper right corner of the slide.</p><p class=\"bold\">What is this specific tissue?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"22\" hint=\"25\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/NER-Strat-Squamous.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"></figure><p>This indicates that the section was taken from the palatine tonsil in the back of the oral cavity. The tonsils have the same general organization of other mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT) in which mainly B-lymphocytes aggregate into lymphoid follicles.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to slides</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/ans/wrong_flow.html","<p>Good try, but note the order of arteries, arterioles, cords, sinusoids, and veins.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'4\'})\">Go back and reassess open circulation order</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/1.html","<p>While working in the emergency room one evening, an unconscious 41-year-old male is rushed into the scene. You are informed he was in a car accident and has a laceration along the lateral margin of the upper left abdominal quadrant between the 10th and 11th ribs resulting in profuse bleeding.</p><p class=\"bold\">Click on the histology slide below that depicts the organ injured.</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'ul\'})\"><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/UL.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'ur\'})\"><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/UR.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></a></div></div><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'ll\'})\"><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/LL.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'lr\'})\"><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/LR.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/2.html","<div class=\"img-split row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><p>Correct! The spleen is located in the upper left abdominal quadrant (left hypochondriac region) in the peritoneal cavity. Notice the <span class=\"purple bold\">white pulp</span> of lymphoid nodules with pale staining germinal centers surrounded by a darker staining marginal zone. The white pulp is surrounded by <span class=\"red bold\">red pulp</span>, the blood-filled stroma of fine reticulin fibers and cells. A thin capsule and the blood-filled stroma contribute to this organ being easily ruptured by abdominal injuries.</p></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/UR.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"></figure></div></div><h3>Histology Scavenger Hunt!</h3><p>Take a screenshot of <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//medsci.indiana.edu/junqueira/virtual/73_bl_5.html\">Slide 73, Spleen, Kornhauser’s Quad</a>, and find the following: <span class=\"bold\">capsule</span>, <span class=\"bold\">central arteriole</span>, <span class=\"bold\">germinal center</span>, <span class=\"bold\">marginal zone</span>, and <span class=\"bold\">red pulp</span>.</p><p class=\"margin-top-lg\">A few medical residents you are shadowing came from Harvard and they are extremely confused as to the function of the spleen (<span class=\"italic\">watch <a class=\"popup-video\" href=\"//www.youtube.com/watch?v=aEi_4Cyx4Uw\">\"What Does the Spleen Do? ft. Harvard Medical School\"</a> for homework if you haven’t seen it already!</span>).</p><p class=\"bold margin-top-lg\">Kindly explain to them 3 functions of this majestic organ.</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>1.)<mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>2.)<mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>3.)<mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'3\'})\">Continue on to contemplate white pulp.</a>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/3.html","<p>You realize the patient may become immunologically compromised by this injury from damage to the white pulp.</p><p class=\"bold margin-top\">What is white pulp and how does it participate in immunity?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"margin-top\">The patient has lost a massive amount of blood and his vital signs are as follows:</p><table id=\"vitals\"><thead><tr class=\"scaffolding\"><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th><th></th></tr><tr><th rowspan=\"2\">Vitals</th><th rowspan=\"2\">Recorded</th><th colspan=\"3\">Do you think the recorded value is:</th></tr><tr><th>High</th><th>Normal</th><th>Low</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr class=\"scaffolding\"><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td><td></td></tr><tr><td>Heart Rate</td><td>104 bpm</td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"0\" value=\"high\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"0\" value=\"normal\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"0\" value=\"low\"></td></tr><tr><td>Blood Pressure</td><td>84/52 mm Hg</td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"1\" value=\"high\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"1\" value=\"normal\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"1\" value=\"low\"></td></tr><tr><td>Respiratory Rate</td><td>18 breaths per minute</td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"2\" value=\"high\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"2\" value=\"normal\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"2\" value=\"low\"></td></tr><tr><td>Body Tempurature</td><td>98.3&deg; F</td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"3\" value=\"high\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"3\" value=\"normal\"></td><td><input type=\"radio\" name=\"3\" value=\"low\"></td></tr><tr><td>Physical Appearance</td><td>Pale Skin and Overt Shock</td><td colspan=\"3\"></td></tr></tbody></table><p class=\"bold margin\">Based on this information, and the previous histological analysis, you decide to:</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'operate\'})\" class=\"sixcol btn btn-default first\">Perform a blood transfusion and CT scan the abdomen and pelvis</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'CTscan\'})\" class=\"sixcol btn btn-default last\">Rush the patient to the operating room for exploratory surgery and possible splenectomy</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/4.html","<ul class=\"clearfix margin-top-lg patient-stats\"><li class=\"clearfix\"><span>Heart Rate</span> <span>104 bpm (tachycardia = increased heart rate; normal = 60-100 bpm)</span></li><li class=\"clearfix\"><span>Blood Pressure</span> <span>84/52 mm Hg (=hypotensive; normal is 120/80)</span></li><li class=\"clearfix\"><span>Respiratory Rate</span> <span>18 breaths per minute (normal is 12-24)</span></li><li class=\"clearfix\"><span>Body Temperature</span> <span>98.3 degrees Fahrenheit (normal is 98.6)</span></li></ul><p>The patient appears hemodynamically unstable (low blood pressure and/or a high heart rate). While the patient is rushed to the OR for exploratory abdominal surgery, you begin to recall the specifics of splenic function, realizing that the massive blood loss was due to the spleen’s unique form of blood circulation.</p><p class=\"bold margin-top-lg\">What is red pulp and what is its function?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"bold margin-top-lg\">Which of the following is the correct order of blood flow in <span class=\"italic underline\">open circulation</span> through the spleen?</p><ol><li class=\"margin-top\">Splenic artery &rarr; trabecular artery &rarr; central arteriole &rarr; penicillar arteriole &rarr; ensheathed capillary &rarr; splenic sinus &rarr; red pulp vein &rarr; trabecular vein &rarr; splenic vein</li><li class=\"margin-top\">Splenic artery &rarr; penicillar arteriole &rarr; central arteriole &rarr; ensheathed capillary &rarr; splenic sinus &rarr; splenic cord &rarr; red pulp vein &rarr; trabecular veins &rarr; splenic vein</li><li class=\"margin-top\">Splenic artery &rarr; trabecular artery &rarr; central arteriole &rarr; penicillar arteriole &rarr; ensheathed capillary &rarr; splenic cord &rarr; splenic sinus &rarr; red pulp vein &rarr; trabecular vein &rarr; splenic vein</li><li class=\"margin-top\">Splenic artery &rarr; trabecular artery &rarr; central arteriole &rarr; penicillar arteriole &rarr; ensheathed capillary &rarr; splenic sinus &rarr; splenic cord &rarr; red pulp vein &rarr; trabecular vein &rarr; splenic vein</li></ol><div class=\"row clearfix margin-top\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'flow1\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Number 1</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'flow2\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Number 2</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'flow3\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Number 3</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'flow4\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Number 4</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/5.html","<p>Nice open circulation flow! <span class=\"bold\">For comparison, write out the steps for <span class=\"underline italic\">closed circulation</span></span> below.</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/NER-pg5.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"></figure><p><span class=\"italic\">Elongated epithelial cells</span> line the walls of splenic sinusoids in the slide above (<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//medsci.indiana.edu/histo/virtual/73_bl_5.html\">Slide 73, Spleen, Kornhauser’s Quad</a>). These cells are oriented in the direction of blood flow, have few contact points, and a discontinuous basal lamina producing spaces between the cells. These spaces allow functional blood cells to reenter the vasculature while surrounding macrophages engulf old or damaged cells.</p><p class=\"bold margin-top-lg\">These elongated, fusiform-shaped endothelial cells of the splenic sinusoids are known as:</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"23\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"bold margin-top-lg\">The spleen is considered a ____________ lymphoid organ.</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'primary\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Primary</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'secondary\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Secondary</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'tertiary\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Tertiary</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/6.html","<p>Correct! The primary lymphoid organs include the bone marrow and thymus, while secondary lymphoid organs include: spleen, lymph nodes, and MALT. Dense aggregations of MALT can be found in:</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>1.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"11\" hint=\"9\" ng-model=\"userAnswer1\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>2.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"12\" hint=\"10\" ng-model=\"userAnswer2\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><label>3.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"13\" hint=\"11\" ng-model=\"userAnswer3\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><p class=\"margin-top-lg\"><span class=\"bold\">Periarteriolar lymphoid sheath (PALS)</span> surrounds the central arteriole playing an important role in immunological surveillance.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/NERpg6.jpg\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"collagen\"><figcaption><p><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//bcrc.bio.umass.edu/histology/?q=node/1418\">https://bcrc.bio.umass.edu/histology/?q=node/1418</a></p><p>CA = central arteriole; PALS = Periarterial lymphatic sheath</p><p>*This is immunohistochemistry, staining actin with FITC (green) and Type II collagen with Rhodamine (Red) and DAPI (Blue) for cell nuclei</p></figcaption></figure><p class=\"bold margin-top-lg\">PALS are formed <span class=\"underline\">mainly</span> from:</p><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'b-lymph\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">B-Lymphocytes</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'t-lymph\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">T-Lymphocytes</a></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-4\"><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'ans\', pageId: \'macrophages\'})\" class=\"btn btn-default\">Macrophages</a></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/7.html","<p>Yes! Cells immediately surrounding the central artery, known as PALS, are largely CD4+ T-cells, although smaller numbers of CD8+ T-cells may also be present.</p><div class=\"img-split row medium clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><p>While waiting for your patient to return from the OR, another case awaits you in the emergency room. A 7-year-old girl presents with a 3-day history of fever and sore throat. Her medical chart indicates she has allergies and repeated tonsillitis. Looking into the girl’s mouth reveals extremely swollen palatine tonsils covered with white exudate.</p></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-6\"><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/teeth.jpg\" class=\"img-responsive\"><figcaption><a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//i.ytimg.com/vi/MPz1RAg9tVU/maxresdefault.jpg\">https://i.ytimg.com/vi/MPz1RAg9tVU/maxresdefault.jpg</a></figcaption></figure></div></div><p>Quickly review your tonsil histology by labeling the slide below, and then <a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'8\'})\">go talk with the patient’s father.</a></p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/NER-Palatine-Tonsil.png\" class=\"img-responsive\"><figcaption>Source: <a target=\"_blank\" href=\"//histology-world.com/photoalbum/displayimage.php?album=60&pid=1607#top_display_media\">http://histology-world.com/photoalbum/displayimage.php?album=60&pid=1607#top_display_media</a></figcaption></figure><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>A.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"28\" hint=\"56\" ng-model=\"userAnswerA\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>B.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"2\" hint=\"57\" ng-model=\"userAnswerB\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>C.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"30\" hint=\"58\" ng-model=\"userAnswerC\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>D.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"31\" hint=\"59\" ng-model=\"userAnswerD\"></mboa-input></label></div></div>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/8.html","<p>After a rapid strep test came back positive, you prescribe antibiotics and decide to discuss the possibility of tonsillectomy with the father. The girl’s father is extremely concerned over the thought of having his daughter’s tonsils removed. You explain to her father that tonsils are a form of secondary lymphatic tissue known as MALT.</p><p class=\"bold\">What does “MALT” stand for and where is it located?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"bold\">What is the function of MALT?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"bold\">How will removal of his daughter’s tonsils affect her health?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p><a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'9\'})\">Go check-in with your first patient</a></p>");
$templateCache.put("a-night-in-the-er/pg/9.html","<p>While checking in with your first patient, you are informed that surgeons performed a splenectomy and that the procedure was successful without any complications.</p><p class=\"bold\">What are some issues your patient should be aware of after spleen removal and how does the body compensate for the loss of splenic function?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"textarea\" ng-model=\"ignore\"></mboa-input></label><p>Congratulations! <a ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Return to the beginning of the case and play again!</a> Try selecting other options to verify you understand <span class=\"italic\">why</span> an answer was incorrect before moving on.</p>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/cortex.html","<p>The cortex is the outer region of a lymph node. The cortex appears dense with numerous lymphoid follicles in a section of tissue that had been antigenetically stimulated.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'5\'})\">Return to meditate on the lymph node regions</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/flow1.html","<ol><li>Afferent lymphatic vessel &rarr; subcapsular sinus &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">medullary sinus</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">trabecular sinus</span> &rarr; efferent lymphatic vessel</li></ol><p>This answer reverses the order of lymph flow through the trabecular and medullary sinuses.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'7\'})\">Return to imagine the flow of lymph through a node</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/flow2.html","<ol start=\"2\"><li><span class=\"bold\">Efferent lymphatic vessel</span> &rarr; subcapsular sinus &rarr; trabecular sinus &rarr; medullary sinuses &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">afferent lymphatic vessel</span></li></ol><p>This option reverses the flow of lymph from afferent lymphatic vessels (think “<span class=\"bold underline\">a</span>fferent” for “<span class=\"bold underline\">a</span>rrive” to the node) to efferent (think “<span class=\"bold underline\">e</span>fferent” for “<span class=\"bold underline\">e</span>xiting” the node).</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'7\'})\">Return to imagine the flow of lymph through a node</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/flow3.html","<ol start=\"3\"><li>Afferent lymphatic vessel &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">high endothelial venule</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">subcapsular sinus</span> &rarr; <span class=\"bold\">trabecular sinus</span> &rarr; efferent lymphatic vessel</li></ol><p>This answer does not correctly flow through the lymph node from cortex, into paracortex, and finally through the medulla.</p><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'7\'})\">Return to imagine the flow of lymph through a node</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/inguinal.html","<p>Lymph from the lower extremity travels through inguinal lymph nodes. Superficial inguinal lymph nodes receive lymph from superficial lymphatic vessels that travel with superficial veins of the leg and thigh. Superficial inguinal lymph nodes drain into the deep lymphatic system, ultimately draining into the thoracic duct.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/ch-23lecturepresentation-26-638.jpg\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"superficial inguinal lymph nodes\"><figcaption><a href=\"//www.slideshare.net/TheSlaps/ch-23lecturepresentation-39270745\">http://www.slideshare.net/TheSlaps/ch-23lecturepresentation-39270745</a></figcaption></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'4\'})\">Go back and reconsider where lymph from the breast drains</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/lymphocytic-vasculitis.html","<p>Lymphocytic vasculitis refers to inflammation of blood vessels due to lymphocyte infiltration into the blood vessel walls. This condition can lead to painful skin welts and may be caused from immune system reactions, pathogenic inflammation, or circulatory system disorders.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/TSL-Lymphocytic-Vasculitis.gif\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"><figcaption><a href=\"//www.ajnr.org/content/26/3/642.figures-only\">http://www.ajnr.org/content/26/3/642.figures-only</a></figcaption></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'8\'})\">Return to contemplate the term for inhibiting lymphatic drainage</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/lymphoma.html","<p>Lymphomas are neoplasms derived from lymphocytes. Different classes are characterized based on the type of cell affected.</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/TSL-Lymphoma.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"\"><figcaption><a class=\"popup-video\" href=\"//www.youtube.com/watch?v=QiM96k0StLw\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QiM96k0StLw</a></figcaption></figure><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'8\'})\">Return to contemplate the term for inhibiting lymphatic drainage</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/medulla.html","<p>The medulla of a lymph node is the innermost region. It contains <span class=\"bold\">medullary</span></p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"37\" hint=\"42\" ng-model=\"userAnswerA\"></mboa-input></label><p class=\"margin-top\">and <span class=\"bold\">medullary</span></p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"38\" hint=\"43\" ng-model=\"userAnswerB\"></mboa-input></label><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'5\'})\">Return to meditate on the lymph node regions</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/primary.html","<p>Note that primary lymphoid organs include the bone marrow and the ____________?</p><label><mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"graded\" answer=\"24\" ng-model=\"userAnswer\"></mboa-input></label><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'2\'})\">Reevaluate lymph node classification as a lymphoid organ</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/spleen.html","<p>The spleen’s parenchyma is organized into distinct regions of red and white pulp, which may closely resemble a cortex and medulla of other organs. Note however, that the red and white pulp of the spleen is somewhat uniformly distributed throughout the organ and not organized into distinct layers seen in the patient’s slide.</p><p class=\"bold\">Can you label the following slide of the spleen?</p><figure><img ng-src=\"{{SITE.baseUrl}}/assets/img/SL-Spleen.png\" class=\"img-responsive\" alt=\"spleen\"></figure><div class=\"row clearfix\"><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>A.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"8\" hint=\"48\" ng-model=\"userAnswerA\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>B.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"32\" hint=\"49\" ng-model=\"userAnswerB\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>C.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"33\" hint=\"50\" ng-model=\"userAnswerC\"></mboa-input></label></div><div class=\"list-item col-sm-3\"><label>D.)<mboa-input type=\"input\" feedback=\"hint\" answer=\"34\" hint=\"51\" ng-model=\"userAnswerD\"></mboa-input></label></div></div><a class=\"back-link\" ui-sref=\"histoCase.pageType.page({pageType: \'pg\', pageId: \'1\'})\">Go back and reassess the patient’s slide</a>");
$templateCache.put("the-suspicious-lesion/ans/stage0.html","<div ng-include=\"\'wrong_stage.html\'\"></div>");
